05:05.055 --> 05:07.599
I never moved there
expecting anything to happen.

05:09.143 --> 05:10.311
I kind of went there
with the attitude

05:10.519 --> 05:12.229
of "Well,
I've got nothing to lose."

05:14.565 --> 05:16.692
Heath arrived at some odd hour,

05:16.900 --> 05:19.737
and he turns around
and looks at me with a big smile

05:19.945 --> 05:21.530
and says "Hello!"

05:21.739 --> 05:22.698
Of course,
the first thing I noticed

05:22.906 --> 05:24.992
was his gigantic smile.

05:25.200 --> 05:29.371
My roommate, Lisa Zane,
knew, in her words,

05:29.580 --> 05:30.622
that he was going to clean up,

05:30.831 --> 05:33.542
meaning
be successful in Hollywood.

05:33.751 --> 05:36.045
I think
she was the first to know that.

05:37.796 --> 05:40.382
Hello.
How was your day?

05:40.591 --> 05:41.925
Oh, it was fun.

05:43.093 --> 05:45.512
There's a book called
The Sentimental Education,

05:45.721 --> 05:49.350
and I feel
that's what he got from Lisa.

05:52.728 --> 05:55.606
Lisa took him
to the Venice Carnevale...

05:58.025 --> 05:59.568
and they shot
8-millimeter film...

06:01.695 --> 06:03.614
and would wear the costumes...

06:05.741 --> 06:06.909
and, to me,

06:07.117 --> 06:08.827
that was a part of what
created him as an actor.

06:11.705 --> 06:13.957
I gave him my friend's script,
10 Things I Hate About You.

06:17.211 --> 06:18.754
He read the script and said,

06:18.962 --> 06:21.048
"I really like
the role of Patrick,"

06:21.256 --> 06:23.509
and I said,
"Isn't Patrick the lead?"

06:23.717 --> 06:26.720
He said,
"Yes, Patrick's the lead,

06:26.929 --> 06:28.514
and that's the part I want,"

06:28.722 --> 06:31.308
and when he came back
from the audition,

06:31.517 --> 06:33.852
he said, "I got Patrick,"

06:34.061 --> 06:36.939
and I was like, "Really?
You got the lead?"

06:37.147 --> 06:41.777
and that's when I realized
that Heath was...

06:41.985 --> 06:42.778
different.

06:42.986 --> 06:44.446
No offence or anything.

06:44.655 --> 06:46.240
I mean, I know everyone
digs your sister,

06:46.448 --> 06:48.409
but, um...

06:48.617 --> 06:49.284
she's without.

07:02.256 --> 07:03.340
Maybe we should do
this another time.

07:18.272 --> 07:19.773
Sometimes
people break through

07:19.982 --> 07:21.775
because of one thing,

07:21.984 --> 07:24.403
whether it's good looks
or talent or timing or...

07:24.611 --> 07:25.904
you know, who knows,

07:26.113 --> 07:28.282
but he sort of had
everything down.

07:30.576 --> 07:33.203
One of the most powerful things
for an actor,

07:33.412 --> 07:34.997
particularly for a man,
is their voice...

07:35.205 --> 07:36.540
I've thrown a football, what,

07:36.748 --> 07:37.833
a few times in my life, so...

07:38.041 --> 07:40.002
And their physicality...

07:40.210 --> 07:42.671
And their, you know,
level of masculinity,

07:42.880 --> 07:44.840
and he had all of those things
in spades.

07:53.682 --> 07:54.933
There was a bunch of kids

07:55.142 --> 07:56.185
staying in a hotel.

07:56.393 --> 07:58.020
Everyone had their own suites,

07:58.228 --> 07:59.480
and he brought everyone
together,

07:59.688 --> 08:02.357
so by the time I got there,
the parties were in his room.

08:02.566 --> 08:05.068
10 Things
was when he really felt

08:05.277 --> 08:07.529
that, "Okay, this is my career.

08:07.738 --> 08:09.198
I'm an actor now."

08:11.116 --> 08:13.243
By then,
he had his agent, Steve.

08:13.452 --> 08:14.411
He knew the industry,

08:14.620 --> 08:15.829
but he didn't really
know the industry.

08:16.038 --> 08:18.582
He'd only been in it
for 18 months.

08:20.626 --> 08:21.710
It was
pretty early in my career.

08:21.919 --> 08:24.004
You know, he was
one of my early clients.

08:24.213 --> 08:27.549
He was looking for people
that he could trust.

08:30.177 --> 08:31.094
Home to sleep.

08:35.557 --> 08:36.725
It was just obvious.

08:36.933 --> 08:38.936
He just had
this great swagger about him.

08:39.144 --> 08:41.438
So how long have
you been acting?

08:41.647 --> 08:43.232
About...

08:44.399 --> 08:45.901
20 years.

08:46.109 --> 08:48.570
How old are you?

08:48.779 --> 08:49.947
20.

08:50.155 --> 08:52.616
You could tell we were going
to be on to something.

08:52.824 --> 08:54.076
So one of the things
that happens

08:54.284 --> 08:56.912
is when you're good
at something in a movie,

08:57.120 --> 08:59.331
everyone offers you
that same thing.

08:59.540 --> 09:01.667
So he did a great job

09:01.875 --> 09:04.962
being in a teen romantic
comedy, basically,

09:05.170 --> 09:07.172
and so anything that, you know,

09:07.381 --> 09:09.299
sort of resembled
10 Things I Hate About You

09:09.508 --> 09:10.884
came his way,

09:11.093 --> 09:14.805
and, of course, that's exactly
what he didn't want to do next.

09:15.013 --> 09:17.516
He wanted to mix it up
and find a new challenge.

09:19.309 --> 09:23.063
That moment
was a very important next step.

09:23.272 --> 09:25.107
"Okay, what do we want
to do next?

09:25.315 --> 09:28.610
What do we really want to do
if we have a choice?"

09:28.819 --> 09:31.071
People in Hollywood,
they don't like to hear "no,"

09:31.280 --> 09:32.489
you know...

09:32.698 --> 09:35.409
and so I had a lot of fun
saying "no."

09:35.617 --> 09:36.702
He was always very friendly.

09:36.910 --> 09:40.122
He never seemed
out of sorts about it,

09:40.330 --> 09:42.165
but he knew what he didn't want.

09:42.374 --> 09:44.960
He was always very appreciative

09:45.168 --> 09:49.381
of coming to a house
full of art and artists.

09:51.717 --> 09:52.759
I am filming
right now.

09:57.014 --> 09:58.307
He got this camera,

09:58.515 --> 10:01.143
and he didn't know what to do
other than to make something.

10:01.351 --> 10:03.604
It wasn't just to film us
and film what we were doing.

10:03.812 --> 10:07.941
He was, like, creating
something straight away.

10:10.110 --> 10:12.446
He always used to say to me,
"Don't forget your camera,"

10:12.654 --> 10:14.698
and I was like, "What am I going
to film between here and there?"

10:14.906 --> 10:18.076
and he was like, "I don't care.
You could film your feet."

10:18.285 --> 10:20.912
But we'd watch
a lot of our videos back.

10:21.121 --> 10:23.749
He was just... curious,
and watching it, and, like,

10:23.957 --> 10:25.375
thinking how
he could do things different.

10:26.918 --> 10:27.669
That's how he learned.

10:27.878 --> 10:29.046
He never studied...

10:29.254 --> 10:30.756
anything, really.

10:30.964 --> 10:33.175
He was self-taught.

10:33.383 --> 10:35.093
He could really see
what he was doing

10:35.302 --> 10:37.346
and how to do that better
or different...

10:38.472 --> 10:39.640
Hmm.

10:39.848 --> 10:40.849
Even if it
was the way he smiled

10:41.058 --> 10:42.100
or where he was looking,

10:42.309 --> 10:45.103
he'd make a lot of things
just for himself,

10:45.312 --> 10:46.563
just to teach himself.

10:48.857 --> 10:50.317
That's right...

10:50.525 --> 10:52.194
<i>And evil
super-villains.</i>

10:52.402 --> 10:53.695
Evil super-villains.

10:53.904 --> 10:55.072
<i>... civilian men and women...</i>

10:55.280 --> 10:56.615
Who?

10:59.534 --> 11:00.911
Got it, boss.

11:01.119 --> 11:01.912
Let's go!

11:02.120 --> 11:04.581
Okay, I've got my mission.

11:04.790 --> 11:05.874
We're at the peephole.

11:06.083 --> 11:09.961
You never know
who's out there waiting.

11:10.170 --> 11:10.962
Okay.

11:20.764 --> 11:21.390
Hey.

11:27.187 --> 11:28.230
Did they know?

12:25.162 --> 12:28.707
Okay, he's not there.

12:28.915 --> 12:30.125
Let's keep on looking.

12:30.333 --> 12:32.002
Down here.

13:13.960 --> 13:16.338
Good Lord.

13:16.546 --> 13:17.923
It was an effort.

13:18.131 --> 13:20.258
Thank God I made it.

13:20.467 --> 13:22.594
What's this? A message?

13:22.803 --> 13:24.513
It must be from him.

13:24.721 --> 13:26.306
Oh, my God...

13:44.074 --> 13:47.410
The screen test for The Patriot
came up with Mel Gibson,

13:47.619 --> 13:49.913
who's the biggest
Australian movie star.

13:50.121 --> 13:51.915
That was one of his idols,

13:52.123 --> 13:54.793
and he loved,
you know, Mad Max and...

13:55.001 --> 13:57.796
It was a huge,
huge thing for him.

13:58.004 --> 14:01.049
It was an actual screen test
and costume on the set

14:01.258 --> 14:02.384
with the main star.

14:04.094 --> 14:05.720
I was halfway
through the second scene

14:05.929 --> 14:07.138
that I had to read for them,

14:07.347 --> 14:09.683
and words were just bluhblbl,
coming out like this,

14:09.891 --> 14:12.853
and so I just stopped
and stood up

14:13.061 --> 14:14.104
and I said, "I'm sorry.
I'm wasting your time."

14:14.312 --> 14:17.107
Heath called me and said,

14:17.315 --> 14:18.733
"They're not calling you
on this one.

14:18.942 --> 14:20.569
I just didn't do well,"

14:20.777 --> 14:22.988
and it was something,
enough there

14:23.196 --> 14:25.866
that Roland Emmerich
and the studio and Mel

14:26.074 --> 14:28.410
all looked at each other
and, I think, said,

14:28.618 --> 14:29.953
"You know, let's take a shot."

14:32.038 --> 14:35.292
So this is, um,
first day shooting.

14:35.500 --> 14:36.793
This is the first day
on The Patriot for me.

14:37.002 --> 14:38.295
I'm looking forward to it.

14:38.503 --> 14:40.380
It's been three months since
I found out I got this job,

14:40.589 --> 14:43.008
and finally, after three months
of sitting around

14:43.216 --> 14:44.092
thinking about it,

14:44.301 --> 14:45.635
I get to go out there
and do it.

14:45.844 --> 14:47.220
This is it.

14:48.763 --> 14:51.016
So...

14:51.224 --> 14:52.893
Blink my eyes,
and it'll be out there.

14:55.562 --> 14:57.314
Guys, guys,
Heath's here, guys.

14:57.522 --> 14:58.356
Everybody look alive.

15:06.197 --> 15:07.490
It was a huge production.

15:09.034 --> 15:11.369
It was a little terrifying

15:11.578 --> 15:14.331
to be in another city
with no friends,

15:14.539 --> 15:17.042
and you're just sitting there
on your own.

15:17.250 --> 15:19.628
It's a lonely life.

15:19.836 --> 15:20.879
Cut.

15:21.087 --> 15:22.797
That's why he took me
to most places

15:23.006 --> 15:24.174
is that it was us.

15:27.385 --> 15:28.511
Hee hee hee hee.

15:30.180 --> 15:31.598
We met riding our bikes

15:31.806 --> 15:32.682
out in the street,

15:32.891 --> 15:35.644
and we just became
best friends.

15:35.852 --> 15:39.147
We felt...
at home together.

15:39.356 --> 15:43.193
You could tell that he was...
he wanted to do a good job.

15:45.153 --> 15:47.572
He was still learning.

15:55.455 --> 15:57.916
I'm not going back.

15:58.124 --> 16:01.252
No, I didn't
expect you would.

16:05.548 --> 16:07.676
That Gates is a damn fool.

16:09.803 --> 16:11.805
He spent too many years
in the British army.

16:12.013 --> 16:14.516
Going muzzle to muzzle with
Redcoats in open field...

16:14.724 --> 16:15.850
it's madness.

16:16.059 --> 16:18.103
He called me one day
from the set,

16:18.311 --> 16:19.896
really upset.

16:22.816 --> 16:26.111
He was having a hard time,
and he was struggling,

16:26.319 --> 16:28.613
just a crisis of confidence.

16:37.872 --> 16:38.790
He was probably, in his head,

16:38.999 --> 16:40.500
he's standing across
from his idol,

16:40.709 --> 16:42.794
acting with Mel Gibson.

16:43.003 --> 16:45.255
For a young Aussie kid,
it was a lot.

16:47.924 --> 16:49.217
He would get caught up
in the fear

16:49.426 --> 16:51.428
of whether or not
he could accomplish

16:51.636 --> 16:53.847
what he wanted to do.

16:54.055 --> 16:55.849
He kind of almost pulled out
of every movie

16:56.057 --> 16:58.309
he ever ended up doing.

17:01.771 --> 17:04.107
It's kind of
a rule of thumb for me

17:04.315 --> 17:05.942
to self-doubt,

17:06.151 --> 17:07.318
always think
that I shouldn't be doing it,

17:07.527 --> 17:08.444
and I don't know how to do it,

17:08.653 --> 17:10.363
and I'm going to fail,

17:10.571 --> 17:12.490
and that I fooled them,

17:12.699 --> 17:14.992
and I always try
and find a way out.

17:19.497 --> 17:20.999
And he got past it,

17:21.207 --> 17:21.915
and Mel was great.

17:22.125 --> 17:23.334
Mel was so generous with him

17:23.542 --> 17:24.711
and really took him
under his wing

17:24.919 --> 17:26.963
and was amazing.

17:27.172 --> 17:28.173
I'm sorry.

17:28.381 --> 17:29.716
Be quiet.

17:29.924 --> 17:31.926
I'll take care of you.
You're going to be all right.

17:32.135 --> 17:33.470
Father...

17:35.638 --> 17:39.267
I'm sorry... about Thomas.

17:43.563 --> 17:44.773
Mel really taught him

17:44.981 --> 17:46.191
how to come in and out
of a character.

17:48.359 --> 17:51.613
He definitely learned
how to relax a little,

17:51.821 --> 17:53.782
rather than building himself
up of, like,

17:53.990 --> 17:56.451
"I've got this scene,
and I've got to do this."

17:58.369 --> 18:01.790
I think Mel was
the first teacher that he had.

18:01.998 --> 18:04.209
Heath used to say to me,
"It's not what Mel says.

18:04.417 --> 18:05.335
It's what he doesn't say."

18:14.844 --> 18:16.096
It's good.
I'm happy to be finished.

18:16.304 --> 18:17.597
It was long.

18:17.806 --> 18:20.391
It was really fun, though,
and they're really great people,

18:20.600 --> 18:24.562
and I'm going to catch
a plane in two hours.

18:24.771 --> 18:27.190
Mel had said,
"Well, I'm taking my jet.

18:27.398 --> 18:28.358
Do you guys want
to come with me?"

18:28.566 --> 18:30.860
Mel Gibson's inviting us
on his jet...

18:34.739 --> 18:35.740
and, all of a sudden,
there we are,

18:35.949 --> 18:37.909
with Mel on his jet,

18:38.118 --> 18:40.370
cruising back to L.A.

18:40.578 --> 18:42.413
It was definitely,
definitely a moment.

18:58.680 --> 19:00.682
So we were always
going on adventures

19:00.890 --> 19:02.725
and looking
for the next adventure

19:02.934 --> 19:04.561
that was exciting and fun.

19:07.272 --> 19:09.149
He'd finished a film.

19:09.357 --> 19:10.275
He had downtime.

19:10.483 --> 19:12.068
We went to Burning Man in '99.

19:20.994 --> 19:21.703
Oh, cool.

19:27.417 --> 19:28.418
We were excited

19:28.626 --> 19:30.003
because we knew
nothing about it.

19:31.171 --> 19:31.796
Cool.

19:34.674 --> 19:37.635
The creativity
that exists there

19:37.844 --> 19:40.638
and the ability to ride bikes
morning, noon, and night...

19:42.265 --> 19:43.183
I think Burning Man

19:43.391 --> 19:44.726
was Heath's favorite place
on Earth.

19:49.355 --> 19:50.356
Do you want
a whiskey, Trevor?

19:50.565 --> 19:51.232
I'd love a whiskey.

19:51.441 --> 19:53.026
Whiskey.

19:53.234 --> 19:55.987
Whiskey and hot dogs.
Nice.

19:56.196 --> 19:58.323
It was a bunch
of half-naked people

19:58.531 --> 20:00.617
and dance music 24-7,

20:00.825 --> 20:04.329
and we fit in really well.

20:11.461 --> 20:14.047
Heath lived every moment
to the fullest.

20:20.345 --> 20:24.766
He was always looking to create
something out of the situation.

20:30.438 --> 20:31.231
Cool...

20:31.439 --> 20:32.523
You see?

20:35.902 --> 20:37.403
He was an artist.

20:37.612 --> 20:39.656
He loved to paint.
He loved to draw.

20:39.864 --> 20:42.742
Cameras
were a big passion of his.

20:42.951 --> 20:44.869
He knew the lighting
that was available.

20:45.078 --> 20:47.789
He knew the speed of the film
that was in his camera

20:47.997 --> 20:50.667
and what he could set it at
without using a light meter.

20:52.835 --> 20:55.630
The cameras were a part of him.

21:10.186 --> 21:12.313
Heath and I
had mutual friends,

21:12.522 --> 21:13.398
so it was a setup.

21:13.606 --> 21:16.109
We met,

21:16.317 --> 21:18.027
and that was it.

21:18.236 --> 21:19.028
That was it.

21:20.488 --> 21:24.284
There were always
cameras around...

21:24.492 --> 21:25.618
a video camera,

21:25.827 --> 21:28.997
or a Polaroid camera,
or the film camera.

21:29.205 --> 21:32.750
I was amazed when I saw
all of the stuff together...

21:35.044 --> 21:37.171
and how many photographs...

21:37.380 --> 21:39.674
I mean, he was
documenting everything.

21:41.759 --> 21:42.677
He was just surrounded

21:42.885 --> 21:46.264
by all of those moments
he was in,

21:46.472 --> 21:47.765
and then surrounded by them,

21:47.974 --> 21:49.684
but then he'd be capturing
the next moment

21:49.892 --> 21:52.437
and the next moment, you know,
and the next moment.

21:54.105 --> 21:55.565
Didn't stop.
It never stopped...

21:59.944 --> 22:02.864
and the way
he was able to be in the moment

22:03.072 --> 22:05.450
and then capture the moment
on the camera...

22:07.118 --> 22:12.290
He just got you
in your most authentic self.

22:12.498 --> 22:14.375
You know, he really got me.

22:14.584 --> 22:17.170
I think that's a beautiful thing

22:17.378 --> 22:20.298
because he's saying, you know,
through his photographs,

22:20.506 --> 22:22.133
"I see you."

22:25.219 --> 22:28.806
The art was more of a need,
almost,

22:29.015 --> 22:33.394
to live in the world
and then capture the world.

22:33.603 --> 22:37.398
He would draw on it
or scratch on it

22:37.607 --> 22:39.317
or use crayon or nail polish.

22:41.152 --> 22:43.905
He wanted to take it all
with him.

22:52.413 --> 22:53.748
That's the only way
I think of him,

22:53.956 --> 22:55.375
with the camera
in the hand.

22:57.168 --> 23:00.088
That was just Heath.

23:04.634 --> 23:06.386
His mates from Perth,

23:06.594 --> 23:08.679
they were
a very close, warm,

23:08.888 --> 23:13.101
loving, you know,
tight group of friends,

23:13.309 --> 23:16.896
and he loved
having them around.

23:17.105 --> 23:19.565
Okay, so I take the 101 south.

23:19.774 --> 23:21.692
He had, like,
15 years of friendship

23:21.901 --> 23:24.529
with kids that we went
to kindergarten with

23:24.737 --> 23:26.197
that we'd graduated
high school with.

23:26.406 --> 23:28.658
Heath always kept them close.

23:30.618 --> 23:32.161
I was privileged
enough to go over

23:32.370 --> 23:35.123
and see how his life was,

23:35.331 --> 23:37.250
and it was
incredibly enticing,

23:37.458 --> 23:38.584
incredibly alluring.

23:38.793 --> 23:40.420
Oh, my goodness,
this has to be, like,

23:40.628 --> 23:43.089
the world
that everyone wants to live.

23:43.297 --> 23:44.674
Kane Manera
from The Strokes...

23:46.259 --> 23:47.510
I think it was the first trip,

23:47.718 --> 23:48.886
driving around, and he says,

23:49.095 --> 23:50.096
"I've got to go
to a friend's house."

23:50.304 --> 23:51.556
Knock on the door,

23:51.764 --> 23:52.640
and he's got this, like,

23:52.849 --> 23:56.185
slightly cheeky look
on his face.

23:56.394 --> 23:57.186
Door opens.

23:57.395 --> 23:59.897
Naomi Campbell answers.

24:00.106 --> 24:02.024
I still have Naomi Campbell
pictures on my wall

24:02.233 --> 24:03.151
at this point.

24:04.861 --> 24:06.237
So I'm doing my best job
of just...

24:07.572 --> 24:09.031
"Hey, how are ya?
Nice to meet you,"

24:09.240 --> 24:10.032
and I'm thinking,

24:10.241 --> 24:11.075
"I guess
this is what Heath does.

24:11.284 --> 24:12.535
This is how it is now.

24:12.743 --> 24:13.953
Just rolls
to Naomi Campbell's house."

24:17.498 --> 24:19.041
Heath! Heath!

24:22.628 --> 24:24.839
Heath's place was renowned

24:25.047 --> 24:27.758
for having a stream

24:27.967 --> 24:30.011
of Australian actors
and whatnots

24:30.219 --> 24:31.053
living there.

24:31.262 --> 24:33.014
Casting directors would ask you,

24:33.222 --> 24:36.184
"And are you one of the Aussies
that lives at Heath's place?"

24:37.852 --> 24:41.939
Yeah, we lived
in Los Feliz in this house

24:42.148 --> 24:43.941
where the doors were just open,

24:44.150 --> 24:46.194
and people would come
and stay.

24:46.402 --> 24:50.615
Joel Edgerton and Heath
were close friends early on,

24:50.823 --> 24:52.867
and he came over,
and Martin Henderson...

24:53.075 --> 24:54.118
I did.

24:54.327 --> 24:55.286
Rose Byrne,

24:55.495 --> 24:57.455
Gregor Jordan,
you know, the director...

24:57.663 --> 24:59.582
You would never know
who's staying at Heath's house.

24:59.790 --> 25:02.752
Everyone and anyone
was welcome, you know?

25:02.960 --> 25:05.588
He had such generosity
of spirit.

25:05.796 --> 25:08.591
It's just miraculous,
the energy...

25:08.799 --> 25:10.801
him, arms open, as always.

25:11.010 --> 25:13.471
The Australian thing,
to me, was like,

25:13.679 --> 25:14.972
yeah, come one, come all,
you know?

25:15.181 --> 25:16.307
Like, hang out.

25:16.516 --> 25:18.309
Let's make this fun.

25:18.518 --> 25:20.686
People would stay a long time,
sometimes.

25:20.895 --> 25:21.687
It was...

25:21.896 --> 25:23.314
a bit longer than necessary,

25:23.523 --> 25:24.941
but, um, but it was fun.

25:25.149 --> 25:28.069
You've flown around the world.

25:28.277 --> 25:31.906
Staying somewhere in L.A.
for a couple of months?

25:32.114 --> 25:34.492
That... phew... costs a lot,

25:34.700 --> 25:39.455
and I had nothing going on
work-wise.

25:39.664 --> 25:40.456
Nothing.

25:40.665 --> 25:42.166
It sort of didn't matter.

25:44.544 --> 25:46.337
Upstairs, they had
a couple turntables.

25:46.546 --> 25:47.755
They had a DJ setup.

25:47.964 --> 25:49.632
"Come in.
We're going to do this.

25:49.840 --> 25:51.801
What do you feel like?
Just chill out.

25:52.009 --> 25:53.302
Oh, this is my record room.
This is the sunroom.

25:53.511 --> 25:55.763
Have you heard of Nick Drake?
You've got to listen to this."

25:55.972 --> 25:57.598
Puts it on, boom....

25:57.807 --> 26:00.434
At his house,
he had a big record collection,

26:00.643 --> 26:01.686
and he could have a big party,

26:01.894 --> 26:04.355
and he would always be
at the music.

26:04.564 --> 26:07.149
Music was definitely something
that was in him

26:07.358 --> 26:08.859
that he... he loved.

26:11.988 --> 26:13.906
With him, it was just
friends to hang out with

26:14.115 --> 26:17.243
and share the journey.

26:17.451 --> 26:21.330
He was very big
on sharing his success.

26:21.539 --> 26:23.374
Heath's place
in L.A. was sort of

26:23.583 --> 26:27.545
a renowned pre-Entourage
kind of entourage house.

26:27.753 --> 26:31.132
In fact,
when I was staying there,

26:31.340 --> 26:34.969
Adrian Grenier was there
at one of these nights.

26:35.177 --> 26:37.972
There was a bit of drinking
and carrying on going on.

26:38.180 --> 26:39.599
Then I often fancy

26:39.807 --> 26:42.768
that he was doing
a bit of research

26:42.977 --> 26:45.938
on a functioning entourage,

26:46.147 --> 26:47.732
'cause Heath wasn't there,

26:47.940 --> 26:49.775
so, you know, "Vinnie,"
as it were,

26:49.984 --> 26:51.402
would've been away
making a film.

26:57.450 --> 26:59.577
There were times
people were there, he wasn't.

26:59.785 --> 27:01.370
I mean, he was on a set
somewhere, working on a movie,

27:01.579 --> 27:02.413
you know, in Europe,

27:02.622 --> 27:04.498
and his house was full.

27:41.077 --> 27:42.161
We were in Prague.

27:42.370 --> 27:44.038
For the first time,
we're really in Europe,

27:44.246 --> 27:45.623
and we're living there.

27:45.831 --> 27:48.709
We're there for pre-production.

27:51.545 --> 27:52.505
Knight's Tale

27:52.713 --> 27:54.674
was an interesting moment
in his career.

27:54.882 --> 27:56.258
Amy Pascal, who runs Sony
at the time,

27:56.467 --> 27:59.970
really, really loved Heath
and appreciated him

28:00.179 --> 28:01.514
and wanted him in everything.

28:03.766 --> 28:04.809
Hyah!

28:05.017 --> 28:05.893
Forward!

28:06.102 --> 28:07.269
Hyah!

28:16.278 --> 28:19.323
Heath really gave
an incredible amount of dignity

28:19.532 --> 28:20.574
to his characters,

28:20.783 --> 28:24.078
even in a film
that's as sort of whimsical

28:24.286 --> 28:25.079
and light, in its way,

28:25.287 --> 28:26.288
as A Knight's Tale.

28:26.497 --> 28:31.168
It's very hard to be
as solid as he was.

28:31.377 --> 28:32.920
You know, at first,
it was a shock.

28:33.129 --> 28:34.422
You know, I read it.

28:34.630 --> 28:37.508
"Queen, 'We Will Rock You,'
rises as they enter the arena."

28:37.717 --> 28:39.552
I think I almost
closed the script on that line

28:39.760 --> 28:41.512
because I was thinking,
oh, it's one of those movies

28:41.721 --> 28:43.139
that's trying to, you know,
mix the two,

28:43.347 --> 28:46.475
but as I read further into it,
it explained itself.

28:46.684 --> 28:48.519
The rock 'n' roll music
destroys any barriers

28:48.728 --> 28:50.354
that are restricting us
to historical truths.

28:50.563 --> 28:52.148
You know, it's a fairy tale.

28:52.356 --> 28:53.649
We want the audience
to walk in there

28:53.858 --> 28:55.234
and to be transported.

29:09.665 --> 29:11.625
We went to Sony
for a marketing meeting

29:11.834 --> 29:12.877
on A Knight's Tale.

29:13.085 --> 29:15.713
Studio president,
studio executives

29:15.921 --> 29:17.965
were all there, doing their job,

29:18.174 --> 29:19.717
excited about the film,
excited about Heath...

29:19.925 --> 29:20.926
very excited about Heath.

29:24.972 --> 29:26.849
The poster and the campaign
was "He Will Rock You."

29:27.057 --> 29:28.851
It was really built on Heath,

29:29.059 --> 29:31.937
you know, the images,
Heath's face...

29:32.146 --> 29:33.147
he looks like a rock star,

29:33.355 --> 29:34.774
and the tag line,
"He Will Rock You,"

29:34.982 --> 29:36.484
and those posters
were all over the city,

29:36.692 --> 29:38.152
all over Los Angeles.

29:38.360 --> 29:40.488
He was, like,
"Whoa, that's my face."

29:40.696 --> 29:43.073
The posters were everywhere.

29:43.282 --> 29:45.534
He knew
that would be projecting him

29:45.743 --> 29:47.953
into the limelight.

29:48.162 --> 29:49.747
There was a moment

29:49.955 --> 29:52.500
where they talked about Heath
was going to go city by city

29:52.708 --> 29:54.627
and talk about the movie,

29:54.835 --> 29:57.379
and, you know, he was going
to be the secret weapon.

29:57.588 --> 30:03.636
William!

30:07.640 --> 30:11.727
I could see him getting more
and more upset, you know?

30:11.936 --> 30:12.937
We were sitting
next to each other,

30:13.145 --> 30:14.438
and I kinda,
out of the corner of my eye,

30:14.647 --> 30:16.982
could tell he was getting very
uncomfortable and fidgeting,

30:17.191 --> 30:20.027
and he finally whispered to me
that he needed to leave,

30:20.236 --> 30:21.862
he needed to get out
of the room for a second,

30:22.071 --> 30:25.282
"Can you excuse me?"
and he got up.

30:25.491 --> 30:27.284
I followed him.

30:27.493 --> 30:29.161
He was in the bathroom.

30:29.370 --> 30:31.413
...Sitting there
just freaking out,

30:31.622 --> 30:33.582
working out what the hell
he was gonna do,

30:33.791 --> 30:35.042
trying to stick to his guns.

30:37.211 --> 30:38.295
There's this thing
in Australia

30:38.504 --> 30:40.589
called the tall poppy syndrome,
you know?

30:40.798 --> 30:43.634
If one grows too high,
whsst,

30:43.843 --> 30:45.970
you get cut down back to size,

30:46.178 --> 30:49.306
and, as an Australian,
you identify with it.

30:49.515 --> 30:51.725
If you do get too successful,

30:51.934 --> 30:53.018
it's sort of,
there's something that's...

30:53.227 --> 30:54.270
You feel ugly.

30:56.397 --> 30:57.398
Being a salesman

30:57.606 --> 30:58.816
and going out
and talking about the movie

30:59.024 --> 31:00.109
and selling the film,

31:00.317 --> 31:01.944
that was
the part of the business

31:02.152 --> 31:04.446
that I think he was
least comfortable with...

31:04.655 --> 31:06.156
Really, really
had a hard time with.

31:06.365 --> 31:08.701
He wanted fame...

31:08.909 --> 31:10.744
And then when he got it,
he didn't want it.

31:12.371 --> 31:16.083
He was mortified,
and he felt owned.

31:16.292 --> 31:17.668
His image, not their image...

31:17.877 --> 31:20.921
Him, his face,
his heart, his soul.

31:21.130 --> 31:24.341
I remember he told me,
"I'm not gonna be that guy.

31:24.550 --> 31:26.302
I have no interest
in being that guy.

31:26.510 --> 31:28.596
I'm not that guy,
and I'll show you."

31:28.804 --> 31:31.599
Hey, do you
know what you did?

31:31.807 --> 31:33.309
Do you know what you did?

31:33.517 --> 31:35.394
Are you listening to me?

31:35.603 --> 31:37.396
Do you know
what you did?

31:37.605 --> 31:39.273
Do you know what you did?

31:39.481 --> 31:40.608
You fucked him up!

31:40.816 --> 31:44.695
He gets to come in,
play this role,

31:44.904 --> 31:46.155
and break your heart.

31:48.365 --> 31:51.744
In the script Monster's Ball,
he felt there was a journey

31:51.952 --> 31:56.415
that would take him
to another place, another level.

31:56.624 --> 32:02.296
He saw something about himself
that attracted him,

32:02.504 --> 32:04.048
that he wanted
to experiment with,

32:04.256 --> 32:05.966
he wanted to play with,

32:06.175 --> 32:08.886
and that gave him
a perfect opportunity.

32:24.234 --> 32:26.654
He's a supporting role,

32:26.862 --> 32:27.780
but I remember him

32:27.988 --> 32:30.407
more than anything else
in the movie,

32:30.616 --> 32:31.450
and he didn't do much.

32:31.659 --> 32:34.370
He was sort of deadpan,
you know?

32:34.578 --> 32:36.538
He didn't do a lot
of busy performances.

32:36.747 --> 32:38.582
That's the power
of Heath Ledger,

32:38.791 --> 32:42.419
even when he was young,
even as a supporting actor,

32:42.628 --> 32:45.005
he will steal the movie,
steal the whole show.

32:45.214 --> 32:47.925
It sort of turned
things a little bit,

32:48.133 --> 32:51.136
and people viewed him
a slightly different way,

32:51.345 --> 32:53.681
a little bit more
of a dramatic actor.

32:53.889 --> 32:56.475
When I read Spider-Man,
I talked to him about it,

32:56.684 --> 32:58.811
and he was almost immediate
that he said,

32:59.019 --> 33:00.020
"That makes no sense for me.

33:00.229 --> 33:02.564
I can't possibly
be Peter Parker."

33:02.773 --> 33:03.941
He was looking, always,

33:04.149 --> 33:06.568
for something that was
gonna be truly challenging,

33:06.777 --> 33:07.903
to try to figure out ways

33:08.112 --> 33:10.572
that he could absolutely
disappear into a character

33:10.781 --> 33:12.199
and almost be unrecognizable.

33:12.408 --> 33:15.035
That's what really drove him.

33:19.373 --> 33:22.292
In his process of picking
what film he was gonna do,

33:22.501 --> 33:24.378
most of that came
from who was directing it.

33:24.586 --> 33:26.547
Shekhar was a director

33:26.755 --> 33:28.632
that he always wanted
to work with.

33:30.384 --> 33:34.221
He recommended Heath,
myself...

33:34.430 --> 33:38.225
We go out in the desert
by ourselves.

33:38.434 --> 33:40.686
You know, just the two of us.

33:43.731 --> 33:46.900
Heath stood there,
looking down the valley,

33:47.109 --> 33:51.447
and we both
just started yelling,

33:51.655 --> 33:55.784
trying to see how far
your voice will carry.

33:55.993 --> 33:57.578
It's you and the desert.

33:57.786 --> 34:00.039
You're forced
to look at yourself.

34:00.247 --> 34:01.707
The impression
you have of yourself

34:01.915 --> 34:02.875
when you look in the mirror

34:03.083 --> 34:04.334
is up to you.

34:04.543 --> 34:07.046
You can see
whatever you want to see,

34:07.254 --> 34:09.965
and you can be
whoever you want to be.

34:12.717 --> 34:14.969
He was really
at the start of a journey

34:15.179 --> 34:18.139
that was a lot more focused
as an artist.

34:20.391 --> 34:22.518
Acting is learning
about the life around you

34:22.728 --> 34:24.228
and the person you are.

34:24.438 --> 34:26.356
You can learn all the techniques
in the world,

34:26.565 --> 34:28.233
but if you know nothing
about life and yourself,

34:28.442 --> 34:30.652
then you're at a loss.

34:30.860 --> 34:32.196
And since
we have to believe it,

34:32.404 --> 34:34.031
for us, for the audience
to believe

34:34.239 --> 34:36.533
what you're putting out there,

34:36.742 --> 34:39.161
you must believe it yourself.

34:39.369 --> 34:44.333
I will not be responsible
for your death.

34:44.541 --> 34:47.168
How could you be responsible
for my death?

